he urban or rural environment on earth, or celestial and meteorological phenomena observed in the sky), biology (the outer appearance of the bodies of humans or animals, or the entrails of sheep), sociology (behavior of people) or others. Based on different divination methods and omen compendia, the question discussed during this workshop was whether the scholars had a scientific approach, presented as religion, or whether Ancient Near Eastern divination should be considered purely religious and that the term "science" is inappropriate in this context. The workshop attracted a large audience and lively discussion ensued. The papers presented in this volume reflect the focus of the sessions during the workshop and are likely to generate even more discussion, now that they are published.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAssyriologyvCongresses. 0aAssyriologyxCongresses. 0aAssyriology. 0aAssyro-Babylonian religionvCongresses. 0aAssyro-Babylonian religionxCongresses. 0aAssyro-Babylonian religion. 0aDivinationxCongressesxMiddle East. 0aDivinationzMiddle EastvCongresses. 0aDivination. 0aRELIGION / ReferencexMiddle EastxConference papers and proceedings. 0aReligion and sciencexCongressesxMiddle East. 0aReligion and sciencezMiddle EastvCongresses. 0aReligion and science. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aCingolo, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Yoram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelnero, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFincke, Jeanette C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFincke, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Ulla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel